content: I am glad to see you all here,
I came in a big hurry indeed.
Before we will move to the analyses part,
let us have a small check

serdyuk, Hannes, leto, yzhnie, fallnavy, SamSite, Red_Zombie, virag, yun_shou, luwenzhe, Alan, Ikon, paradise, Morden, tianxia, yyfcsd, shuwang, ouyang, pengyu, dittp, sosei, mayhem, Intotherenju, lingdodo, coco_yuang, whte.
Today I wish to introduce to you another strong renju legend.
Have you heard of the player Nikolay Mihailov?
He was one of the greatest renju players, very very talented,
Unfortunately he died in 1995, so we cannot meet him anymore.
But before that, he was very strong,
He has won the Russian High League,
He was the participant in the first WC in 1989,
He and I played many times in tournaments during those years 1990-1995
1995, I didnt even know renju at that time. sigh
I dont remember the total score between us,
but I believe he won more than me
Today I present a game which was played just a few months before he died,
and it was a beautiful game,
and the loser was me of course
So, Mihailov black, and I was white
At that time, I was the fan of the stronger 5th move, playing it as white
I had been quite successful as white there,
but Mikhailov is different class player - his moves were very powerful.
you play all gamas as white in WC
oh that was not a WC game
we played in more tournaments than just WCs
the game I show now comes from Baltic Cup 1995,
his game was always impressive because he used his talent and calculation ability more than theoretical preparation
Most of you know this variant.
I had prepared some gambling variants here for white.
However, I had to face a surprise quickly.
The traditional move would have been 9-h9
What should white do here? Any ideas?
In that game I used h11,
I dont know, if other moves could be better or not.
The worst thing for me was,
and I had to count on my skill only.
So, he had a great advantage here in that aspect.
Is it good or bad move?
those who say good, can you explain why good?
connect and line and white line wrong now
inner, but very useful,cut white and connect black
cut white and make one two
but i think is good because interrupt w activities
h6 is black good point but white can not occupy the point
blocks white's potential connection and give black some good points
creates possibilites for black on lower side
i also thing is from this aspect:
since white has certain activity in move 12,
black likely has to choose between f9 and h9.
In that case, we can just compare them
Move f9 is an outside stone,
Since black cannot win in the left wing alone,
he will need to use both left and right wings,
but the f9 stone does not much make the right wing any better,
and if the right side is poor,
then white may defend more bravely
but its much more difficult to find continuation,
for the reason I mentioned above.
If we change the 13th move to h9,
then despite being an inside stone, the h9 makes the lower and right wing very powerful.
Now, black can play to the right wing safely,
this is exactly what black should do here
which means, white must play passively,
and will lose very soon anyway
So, you can understand better why h9 was a good move.
In that game, I played 14 here, to h6.
What do you think about that move?
if i was the black ,maybe i will choose F7 to start attack
the word 'dangerous' always confuses me when we use it in renju game, because grammatically it should mean "move that puts opponent in danger"... but often people mean dangerous as "being in danger"
so, the word dangerous is most of the time misused
that is why i rarely use it myself, in order not to confuse you
and i think sometime ,brave is dangerous
so, please remember, dangerous means, putting someone in danger, threatning,
and if talking about self danger, we can use word "risky" move instead
Chinese translate wei xian with dangerous
hayakawa said: no dangerous no win
but many of us speaks often that "black has died"
the question is : how black could attack?
we know in the game by Mr. Nakamura, he always let his opponent to move the dangerous move
lingdodo, did he say it in english?
its not risky move at all
in fact, it is a safe and passive move
i dont think it's very strong
maybe it is only a surprise move
i think the white has power defense
i remember that  mr nakaruma won one game of this variant  long ago
I spent lots of time here
At that time, I had no game records about Japanese games, other than WC games,
After long thinking, I played 18 here.
if let me choose, i will choose J12
I thought of this move as an optimal defense.
why left not right? show us, pls
The idea of move 17 is to bring the force to the left wing direction.
This black stone gives extra support
and now you can see the usefulness of the support
so you understand why i played 18 there
I had to defend left side,
and at the same time, i needed to worry about upper side
so move 18 is the uppest possible move
Now, black will begin final attack on the right win
Lets say if I block here
That is why I had no choice
I started to belive I may be able to defend,
but then another magic move came
Lets say, if I block here,
and I was about to resign
but then I resigned without waiting his next move.
So, I had no defense here.
But biggest shock came after I resigned,
when he announced that our game was 100% copy of the Nakamura-Yoshizawa game from 1980
and I had played all white moves exactly as Yoshizawa
what time was you find this?:)
If I had known the history at that time,
May be he not used his talent :)
I would not get that loss
So it is Nakamura who beat you in this game :)
Right after game, he told me that Nakamura-Yoshizawa game was same
he spent lots of time in every move,
only way to beat you perhaos...
all his conclusions were that there are no better moves than those that Nakamura already made,
so he was forced to follow them
and about me, I didnt know anything at all,
Two great players team vs Ando
but the fact that all my moves, including 18, 24 etc, were all same as Yoshizawa,
that strongest players tend to find optimal solutions in game,
and so their moves will match,
even if they dont see each others games.
renju is a very logical game,
because only logic can make two game become same like this
thats how i felt after game
its like two dimensions of worlds
sometimes you may wonder what the player is thinking during game, or afraid of, or how calculates, how makes decisions..
and having gone through all these steps with identical game,
i can say that i will know how Yoshizawa must have felt and thought in his game
and maybe i would have never known his feeling,
if this game didnt happen in 1995.
Because the game record analyses never gives us perfect closeness in emotion,
Mihailov was a great fan of Yoshizawa.
He former USSR, he was the only player who had so many great tales and stories about Japanese legends.
So, he told me a lot about Yoshizawa,
and about his match with Nakamura.
He spoke in very passionate manner,
and I admired him for his passion.
From Mihailov, I heard the first history things about Japanese,
the old Japanese games were published in database,
and more people got to know them.
but at that time, in 1995, he was perhaps the only foreigner who had the records of the old match from 1980.
and I became very very interested in renju history.
And I am glad I had a chance to introduce MIhailov to you today.
So, you know there was such a great man,
who most of the time won me.
we can see more of his games,
i have played all the changes of 29-J6
let me show how the game Nakamura-Yoshizawa ended,
Yoshizawa played a few more moves here before he resigned.
I realize that there is more in renju than just theory.
I was so fixed in my thinking,
assuming people always play theoretical moves,
but as you see from Nakamura's move 9,
some may even be better than theoretical moves.
I tried to analyse and find defense at some point,
So, this game taught me to see things in new angle,
to be prepared for any possibility,
So, I began to think more critically about moves that I play and variants that I prepare for tournaments.
If you ask, is move 9-j9 black win,
I just can say that when I analysed it in 1995,
I could not find anything good for white.
I could not find how should white play to avoid loss.
Of course, all 14th moves must be analysed before saying surely.
thx RT, i have to leave, bye everyone
But from this moment, all was sure win.
Move 18 must be played to f10
but here i spent some time after game
and could not find any defending 24
So, it was a nice lesson to me back in 1995, and a good lesson for you today!
So, its a good time to end todays lesson! See you next week, dear friends!

Alan, coco_yuang, dittp, fallnavy, Hannes, Ikon, Intotherenju, leto, lingdodo, luwenzhe, mayhem, Morden, ouyang, pengyu, Red_Zombie, SamSite, serdyuk, shuwang, sosei, tianxia, virag, whte, yun_shou, yyfcsd, yzhnie.
